comments.body:
> Is `adb` in the `$env:Path`? If not you should run it with a relative or full path even if it is in the current directory:

adb has been added to the system environment variables;
But when I run `$env:Path`, something very strange happens:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42903751/157254318-fc902352-5e43-4dae-9034-d3cfeec10537.png)

As you can see in the picture:
The image above shows me opening windows terminal by right clicking on the Microsoft icon;
The picture below shows me right-clicking on a folder to open windows terminal;

The above picture shows the environment variable with the directory where adb is located, but the below picture does not, which is probably why the above picture can invoke adb through the command line normally.

> I suspect a reboot would eliminate this issue.

You are right, after restarting the computer, right click in a random folder and open the terminal, you can invoke adb through the command line normally;
But it's strange, isn't it true that the environment variables in windows take effect in time? This is the first time I've encountered an environment variable that requires a restart of the computer to work, a bug in windows 11?
